		<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/509d7c43f9707abcdf8553584861c3d9?s=55&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D55&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-55 photo' height='55' width='55' />		<span class="authorname">HM</span>
		</div>
				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
		<a href="http://oneparticularkitchen.com/2009/05/19/salsa/#comment-26770">
		March 18th, 2011 at 11:54 pm</a>
        <span class="comment-reply-link"><a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2009/05/19/salsa/?replytocom=26770#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-26770", "26770", "respond", "373")'> &middot; Reply</a></span>		 		</div>
		<p>Glad I saw the person mention using a pressure cooker to can this- my cousin does just that, and I&#8217;ll have to sugggest this recipe to her as a way to preserve all the produce she&#8217;s sure to have (huge garden in the works, tomatoes, peppers, herbs, veggies, fruits etc&#8230;)</p>
<p>I thought that it would be ok to can them in the pressure cooker, good to have confirmation. She&#8217;s already started canning things- meat she finds on sale, marmalade to use up a huge bag of oranges she had given to her etc&#8230; The meat seemed weird to me, but she said it&#8217;s good as long as you use the pressure cooker to do it, the heat gets high enough to kill any possible thing.</p>
		</div>
</li>
